Single page application based on AngularJS.

Key tasks:
▪ considerable rewriting of key system module that loads and stores user data and renders infinite time scroll with user events;
▪ development of GUI to manipulate time and duration of user events with drag-n-drop and other mouse driven events;
▪ development of map route builder module (based on Google Maps Directions API) with many optimizations including route data compression and improved text directions and map rendering speed;
▪ transfer from backend to frontend a module that builds user locations and time zone changes over time;
▪ development of fast calendar GUI with infinite scroll that is accessible from any date and time pickers forms;
▪ optimization of application loading time and overall performance and memory consumption;
▪ development of credit card payment form with all necessary validations;
▪ integration and promotion of different code linters and code style conventions;
▪ rewriting application from CoffeeScript to modern JavaScript and then to TypeScript.

The automated system to digitalize paper vital records of civil status.

Key accomplishments:
▪ Angular sub application to mark down areas for vital records parts processing;
▪ integration with browser NPAPI plugin to connect our client side application to the scanner;
▪ integration with government web services base on SOAP to provide them with vital records data;
▪ refactoring of the core Ruby on Rails application to make it suitable for similar needs (processing other kinds of paper documents).

That was my main project that I worked on during my last year in university and afterwards when I become a freelancer working on small websites mostly as a frontend developer. With mentorship from my colleague and friend Lev Levin I worked to make the best information website about entertainment, educational and other events/activities in our city. The database was automatically populated from different sources (mostly including our city venues websites) with very little manual work from us.

Responsibilities:
▪ Python/Django and front-end development;
▪ database scheme design;
▪ UI prototyping for our designer.

Key accomplishments:
▪ integration with many websites: via API or just raw HTML parsing if there was no API;
▪ providing API for Yandex.Afisha (one of the biggest information sources on events in Russian cities);
▪ customized Django Admin page with many improvements for fast search, automatic data updating and monitoring;
▪ clean and fast Python code that was run on our web server with the help of gunicorn and nginx proxy;
▪ database scheme that suited our needs for storing data about different kinds of events;
▪ cross-browser website that looked good in all browsers that time.

I was a consultant web developer in a startup called TolkoNikomu - a mix of Twitter and eBay for sales managers in textile, clothing and footwear industry in Russia. My primary goal was to make a web application in a very short term - only 2 months for a beta, and some more weeks to make it production ready. I used my well-know stack including Django framework and 

We worked closely with UI specialist Mikhail Shatrov to make design modern and beautiful while keeping it as simple as possible to meet the deadline. I was also a leader in team with two intern programmers from Ivanovo State Power University who needed to learn how production programming happens. Dmitry Terrov was one of them, he helped me a lot and I hope that he learned something from me.

Key accomplishments:
▪ we've made everything on time that allowed our founders to start validating the business idea;
▪ I made the team work possible and even productive using agile techniques and modern instruments like Trello;
▪ UI and UX were much better than they could be when developing in that hurry;
▪ all Python code was covered with unit-tests, some tests were made with Gherkin/Cucumber format;
▪ while the app was primarily server based, I made a lot of improvements on a client side for fast operations (+1, follow/unfollow, and similar) that didn't require page reloading;
▪ front-end code was modular and component-based (before this became a trend).
